snippet.title: Twitter kills #Music, adds tweet view count
snippet.description: The social network retreats from its failed music service and tests a way to show how many people read your tweets. Also, Google adds new party tricks to the Chromecast with the Photowall app.

snippet.title: Microsoft's Kinect recruited as Korean border guard
snippet.description: The motion-detection system aims to catch people crossing the border between the two Koreas, says Kotaku.

snippet.title: Korean supplier said to be testing 65-inch Apple iTVs
snippet.description: A South Korean manufacturer is making samples of an Apple TV set based on OLED technology, a report claims.

snippet.title: Samsung software efforts to enlist South Korean soldiers
snippet.description: Samsung has looked towards the military to provide the firm's next generation of software engineers.

snippet.title: Samsung Galaxy S5 could be stung by Korean carrier ban
snippet.description: The Galaxy S5 will go on sale smack in the middle of a ban that will keep Korean carriers from adding new customers or allowing existing customers to upgrade phones.

snippet.title: LG's 5.5-inch Gx gets Korean launch
snippet.description: The Gx comes across as a supersized LG G2, with a 13-megapixel camera and a quad-core Qualcomm Snapdragon 600 processor.

snippet.title: BlackBerry to customers: 'You can continue to count on us'
snippet.description: The struggling Canadian smartphone maker pens an open letter, saying that it will work through the challenges facing it.

snippet.title: Americans can't count, and not so good at tech -- report
snippet.description: According to a report by the OECD, America comes only above Italy and Spain in math ability. We're below average at technological problem-solving. Is this surprising?
